"Auburn","county":"Cayuga","state":"New York","country":"United States","cause":"heart disease (sudden, at railroad station)"},"prominent_name_reason":"Justice Frank Arthur Hooker (1844-1911) — Michigan Supreme Court Chief Justice 1893-1911, 18 years, 1,700 opinions. Self-described 8th-generation descendant of Rev. Thomas Hooker. Stonemason who self-educated into the law; reached highest court of Michigan. Died en route to ABA conference in Chicago, 1911.","political_offices":[{"title":"Superintendent of Schools","jurisdiction":"Eaton County, Michigan","dates":"1867-1869"},{"title":"Prosecuting Attorney","jurisdiction":"Eaton County, Michigan","dates":"1873-1877","notes":"Two consecutive terms."},{"title":"Circuit Judge","jurisdiction":"5th Judicial Circuit, Michigan","dates":"1878-1893","notes":"Appointed by Gov. Charles Croswell 1878."},{"title":"Justice / Chief Justice","jurisdiction":"Michigan Supreme Court","party":"Republican","dates":"1893-1911","duration_years":18,"notes":"Chief Justice 1893, 1902, 1903. Authored ~1,700 opinions. Died in office, heart failure, Auburn NY, Jul 10, 1911."}],"gender":"male","marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X01425","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":1,"spouse_name":"Emma Elizabeth Carter","date_year":1868,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1909}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["law","politics","education"],"notable_blurb":"Michigan Supreme Court Chief Justice; 1,700 opinions"},"number_of_marriages":1,"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Frank Arthur Hooker","first_name":"Frank","last_name":"Hooker","middle_name":"Arthur","married_names":[],"gender":"male"},"residence":{"city":"Charlotte","county":"Eaton","state":"Michigan","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"plot_notes":"Mount Hope Cemetery, Lansing, Ingham County, Michigan."},"education":[{"school_name":"University of Michigan Law Department","graduation_year":1865}],"career":[{"role":"Apprentice stonemason","start_year":1860,"notes":"Began as apprentice stonemason at age sixteen; taught himself mathematics, history, and Latin in spare hours."},{"role":"Attorney (private practice)","start_year":1865,"end_year":1873,"notes":"Practiced Bryan OH 1865-66, then Charlotte MI 1866-."},{"role":"Superintendent of Schools","organization":"Eaton County, Michigan","start_year":1867,"end_year":1869},{"role":"Prosecuting Attorney","organization":"Eaton County, Michigan","start_year":1873,"end_year":1877,"notes":"Two terms."},{"role":"Judge","organization":"Michigan 5th Judicial Circuit Court","start_year":1878,"end_year":1893,"notes":"Appointed by Governor Charles Croswell in 1878."},{"role":"Justice (elected)","organization":"Michigan Supreme Court","start_year":1893,"end_year":1911,"notes":"Chief Justice 1893, 1902, and 1903. Served 18 years on Supreme Court. Authored approximately 1,700 opinions across 73 volumes of Michigan Reports. Participated in 8,300+ decisions. Judicial philosophy described by fellow Justice Claudius B. Grant as 'shortest cut, based upon reason, common sense and the experience of centuries.'"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"Self-taught from stonemason to Chief Justice","body":"He began as an apprentice stonemason at sixteen, with no formal schooling beyond that — but taught himself mathematics, history, and Latin in spare hours. He entered the University of Michigan Law Department and graduated in 1865 at twenty-one. Twenty-eight years later he was elected to the Michigan Supreme Court, where he served as Chief Justice three times."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Wrote approximately 1,700 Michigan Supreme Court opinions","body":"He authored roughly seventeen-hundred opinions across seventy-three volumes of Michigan Reports during eighteen years on the bench. He participated in 8,300-plus decisions over that span. Fellow Justice Claudius B."}],"slug":"frank-hooker-1844"},"H00350":{"id":"H00350","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"generation_from_john_talcott":4,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1746,"month":8,"day":24,"city":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1813,"month":5,"day":29,"city":"Herkimer","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00115","mother_id":"I00054"},"tags":["new_york_migration","not_yet_fully_entered","hooker_talcott_descent"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 350"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00321","children_ids":["H00802","H00803","H00804","H00805","H00806","H00807","H00808"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1769,"date_month":8,"date_day":2,"location_country":"United States"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"The firm's failure drove him from Connecticut","body":"As a partner in Hooker and Chaffee, he helped provision the Continental Army before French and Spanish spoliations brought the firm down after the war. He removed to Sackett's Harbor, New York, and later died at Herkimer; his wife Elizabeth survived him by just six months."}],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST070","institution_blurb":"Partner in the firm; dispersed to western New York after its failure."}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Horace Hooker","first_name":"Horace","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"horace-hooker-1746"},"X00321":{"id":"X003